σ2 = (11.56 + 0.16 + 0.36 + 0.16 + 12.96)/5 = 5.04

STANDARD DEVIATION
Standard deviation is the square root of the variance. So from the previous example:
σ2 = 5.04
σ = square root of 5.04 = 2.24
So the standard deviation of (1,4,5,4,8) is 2.24
This is usually used as a way to identify outliers. Data points that lie more than one standard deviation from the mean can be considered unusual.
You can talk about how extreme a data oint is by talking about "how many sigmas" away from teh mean it is. 

POPULATION VS SAMPLE
If you are working with a sample of data instead of an entire data set (the entire population) then you want to use the "sample variance" instead of the "population variance".
For N samples, you divide the squared variances by N-1 instead of N, where N is the number of data points. 
So, in our example, we computed the population variance like this:
σ2 = (11.56 + 0.16 + 0.36 + 0.16 + 12.96)/5 = 5.04
But assuming that the data was just a sample of a larger dataset, the sample variance would be:
S2 = (11.56 + 0.16 + 0.36 + 0.16 + 12.96)/4 = 6.3

